<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii"></span>

#### <span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p0.1"></span>Chapter I.

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p1"></span>*The author distinguishes the faith
from the errors of Pagans,* <span id="fr_1669"></span>[1670](#fn_1669.md)
*Jews, and Heretics, and after explaining the significance of the names
“God” and “Lord,” shows clearly the difference of Persons in Unity of
Essence.* <span id="fr_1670"></span>[1671](#fn_1670.md) * In dividing the
Essence, the Arians not only bring in the doctrine of three Gods, but
even overthrow the dominion of the Trinity.*

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p4"></span>6. <span class="sc"><span
id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p4.1"></span>Now</span> this is the declaration of our
Faith, that we say that God is One, neither dividing His Son from Him,
as do the heathen, <span id="fr_1671"></span>[1672](#fn_1671.md) nor
denying, with the Jews, that He was begotten of the Father before all
worlds, <span id="fr_1672"></span>[1673](#fn_1672.md) and afterwards born
of the Virgin; nor yet, like Sabellius, <span
id="fr_1673"></span>[1674](#fn_1673.md) confounding the Father with the
Word, and so maintaining that Father and Son are one and the same
Person; nor again, as doth Photinus, <span
id="fr_1674"></span>[1675](#fn_1674.md) holding that the Son first came
into existence in the Virgin’s womb: nor believing, with Arius, <span
id="fr_1675"></span>[1676](#fn_1675.md) in a number of diverse
Powers, <span id="fr_1676"></span>[1677](#fn_1676.md) and so, like the
benighted heathen, making out more than one God. For it is written:
“Hear, O Israel: the Lord thy God is one God.” <span
id="fr_1677"></span>[1678](#fn_1677.md)

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p14"></span>7. For God and Lord is a name of
majesty, a name of power, even as God Himself saith: “The Lord is My
name,” <span id="fr_1678"></span>[1679](#fn_1678.md) and as in another
place the prophet declareth: “The Lord Almighty is His name.” <span
id="fr_1679"></span>[1680](#fn_1679.md) God is He, therefore, and Lord,
either because His rule is over all, or because He beholdeth all things,
and is feared by all, without difference. <span
id="fr_1680"></span>[1681](#fn_1680.md)

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p18"></span>8. If, then, God is One, one is the
name, <span id="page_203">p. 203</span> <span
id="iv.iv.iii.ii-Page_203"></span>one is the power, of the Trinity.
Christ Himself, indeed, saith: “Go ye, baptize the nations in the name
of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit.” <span
id="fr_1681"></span>[1682](#fn_1681.md) In the *name,* mark you, not in the
*names.*” <span id="fr_1682"></span>[1683](#fn_1682.md)

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p21"></span>9. Moreover, Christ Himself saith: “I
and the Father are One.” <span id="fr_1683"></span>[1684](#fn_1683.md)
“One,” said He, that there be no separation of power and nature; but
again, “*We are,*” that you may recognize Father and Son, forasmuch as
the perfect Father is believed to have begotten the perfect Son, <span
id="fr_1684"></span>[1685](#fn_1684.md) and the Father and the Son are One,
not by confusion of Person, but by unity of nature. <span
id="fr_1685"></span>[1686](#fn_1685.md)

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p25"></span>10. We say, then, that there is one
God, not two or three Gods, this being the error into which the impious
heresy of the Arians doth run with its blasphemies. For it says that
there are three Gods, in that it divides the Godhead of the Trinity;
whereas the Lord, in saying, “Go, baptize the nations in the name of the
Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit,” hath shown that the
Trinity is of one power. We confess Father, Son, and Spirit,
understanding in a perfect Trinity both fulness of Divinity and unity of
power. <span id="fr_1686"></span>[1687](#fn_1686.md)

<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p27"></span>11. “Every kingdom divided against
itself shall quickly be overthrown,” saith the Lord. Now the kingdom of
the Trinity is not divided. If, therefore, it is not divided, it is one;
for that which is not one is divided. The Arians, however, would have
the kingdom of the Trinity to be such as may easily be overthrown, by
division against itself. But truly, seeing that it cannot be overthrown,
it is plainly undivided. For no unity is divided or rent asunder, and
therefore neither age nor corruption has any power over it. <span
id="fr_1687"></span>[1688](#fn_1687.md)

