<span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p3"></span> The Latin word is *natura,* which, at
first sight, seems less abstruse and metaphysical than the Greek <span
class="Greek"><span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p3.1"></span>οὐσία</span>, or <span
class="Greek"><span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p3.2"></span>ὑ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="iv.iv.iii.ii-p3.3"></span>πόστασις</span>, or
the Latin *essentia* and *substantia,* though it is not really so. A
man’s *natura*, nature, is what he is at and from the beginning; “change
of nature” means not an absolute change, but a reformation, a new
guidance and treatment of tendencies, passions, powers—some receiving a
precedence denied them before, others being suppressed and put in
subjection. So God’s “nature” is what He is from and to all eternity, in
Himself, unchangingly and unchangeably.

